U.S. drilling activity slowedsignificantly in Texas and Oklahoma last week, resulting in thenumber of U.S. active rotary rigs to plunge by 35 to a total of766, against 1,212 working rigs one year ago, Hughes Tool Co.said.    Most of the decrease came among rigs used for onshoredrilling, which dropped to a total of 671 from last week's 707.A total of 78 rigs were active offshore and 17 were working ininland waters during the week, Hughes Tool said.    Among individual states, Texas lost 23 working rigs,Oklahoma dropped by 13, Louisiana was down three and New Mexicodropped by one. Wyoming, Kansas and California reported gainsof six, five and four rigs, respectively.    In Canada, the rig count was up 16 to 180, against 398 oneyear ago. Reuter&#3;